# DDTree on asym3 KV: b12-k2 is a net win on prose + instruct

_Measured 2026-04-23, dflash @ e5534e4, 27B Qwen3.5 MQ4 target + 919 MB true-MQ4 draft, 7900 XTX gfx1100._

## Headline

With the production KV mode (asym3), DDTree-batched at `--ddtree-budget 12 --ddtree-topk 2`
beats linear DFlash on **prose (+28% tok/s, +2.5× τ)** and **instruct (+29% tok/s, +2.4× τ)**.
Code still loses (linear asym3 already hits τ=7.57, no headroom).

Prior 2026-04-22 "null result" and today's earlier sweep were measured on `--kv-mode q8` (legacy
default) — that understated DDTree's value on the real production KV mode. The user flagged it
("when you test ddtree are you testing with q8kv or asym3?") and the rerun on asym3 flipped the sign.

## Full matrix (--max 192, --ctx 2048)

| prompt   | kv     | linear tok/s (τ) | b8-k2 tok/s (τ) | **b12-k2** tok/s (τ) | b12-k2 fast/slow |
|----------|--------|-----------------:|----------------:|---------------------:|:----------------:|
| code HE/0 | q8    | 124 (5.47)       | 98 (5.16)       | 102 (6.22)           | 19/8             |
| code HE/0 | asym3 | **154 (7.57)**   | 90 (5.13)       | 90 (6.00)            | 4/3              |
| prose     | q8    | 38 (0.84)        | 55 (2.90)       | 60 (3.39)            | 26/18            |
| prose     | asym3 | 59 (1.97)        | 67 (3.83)       | **76 (4.94)**        | 17/16            |
| instruct  | q8    | **76 (2.84)**    | 55 (2.78)       | 59 (3.29)            | 27/18            |
| instruct  | asym3 | 54 (1.69)        | 47 (2.43)       | **70 (4.08)**        | 26/13            |

Prompts:
- **code**: HumanEval/0 (`has_close_elements` signature + docstring).
- **prose**: Roman Empire decline continuation, no chatml.
- **instruct**: "Explain in three paragraphs why the Roman Empire declined..." with chatml.

## Secondary finding: asym3 is a regression for linear DFlash on instruct-style prompts

- q8 linear instruct: 76 tok/s / τ=2.84
- asym3 linear instruct: 54 tok/s / τ=1.69 — **-28% tok/s, -40% τ**

Code and prose don't show this regression (asym3 wins on both for linear). The 3-bit K quantization
may be biting the instruct prompt-answering token distribution in a way structured code/prose
tokens shrug off. DDTree b12-k2 recovers past the asym3-linear floor (70 vs 54) and even
approaches the q8-linear ceiling (70 vs 76).

Worth investigating separately — a single-model sidecar / per-genre KV-mode dispatch may be
the right response if this reproduces on more instruct-style prompts.

## Why b12-k2 beats b8-k2 (and why the picture flipped from q8)

- On q8 KV, the draft's native τ on prose is 0.84. b8-k2 (depth=7) is already wide enough to
  produce strong τ lift (0.84 → 2.90).
- On asym3 KV, draft τ on prose is 1.97 — already 2× the q8 baseline. b8-k2 has less room to
  add value; a deeper tree (b12-k2, depth=11) finds more acceptance at committed depths ≥ 7.
- b12-k2 pays more forward cost per cycle but fires slow on fewer cycles (prose asym3:
  17 fast / 16 slow = 52% fast vs b8-k2's 25/15 = 63% fast — b12 trades slow-fire rate for
  tree size and wins on wall-clock because the bigger trees find longer accepted chains).
- Paper defaults (b60-k8) are catastrophic at 27B on gfx1100 regardless of KV mode — tree forward
  at 60 tokens dominates everything.

## Configuration recommendation

Add per-genre DDTree preset to dflash_spec_demo / daemon:
- **code detected**: linear + asym3 (fastest at τ=7.57)
- **prose / instruct**: `--ddtree-batched --ddtree-budget 12 --ddtree-topk 2` + asym3

Genre detection heuristic: first-response-block tokens. If within the first ~16 emitted tokens
the ratio of natural-language tokens (spaces + lowercase letters + punctuation) exceeds ~75%,
switch to DDTree b12-k2. Otherwise stay linear. Can also be set per-model-config via the
existing `per_model_config.json` or exposed as a CLI/daemon toggle.

Opt-in flag for now pending slow-path kill + speed/quality gate:
```
HIPFIRE_DDTREE_DEFAULT=1  # opts b12-k2 + asym3 on for prose/instruct workloads
```

## Slow-path-kill still unlocks more

b12-k2 fires slow on 35-50% of cycles on prose/instruct. Each slow cycle = full target forward
(~40-50 ms). Killing it via **Path A (KV-only mini-forward + tape gather)** — documented
separately in `docs/plans/ddtree-kv-race-slow-path-kill.prd` — projects another +15-25% tok/s
on prose/instruct. Timeline: 4-8 hours implementation + test, one session.

## Full 33-prompt HumanEval sweep (code-only, --max 128 ctx 2048)

| config              | mean tok/s | median | p10    | p90    | mean τ | median τ | min τ | max τ |
|---------------------|-----------:|-------:|-------:|-------:|-------:|---------:|------:|------:|
| **linear asym3**    | **128.67** | 126.73 | 100.82 | 159.08 | **6.10** | 6.00   | 2.53  | 10.55 |
| b12-k2 asym3        | 84.49      | 84.09  | 62.56  | 102.34 | 5.39    | 5.33    | 2.56  | 7.87  |
| Δ                   | **−34%**   | −34%   | −38%   | −36%   | −12%    | −11%    |       |       |

Confirms: **DDTree is a loss on pure-code (HumanEval) workloads** at 27B asym3. Linear is the
right config. The prose/instruct wins above are genre-specific.

Raw per-prompt output: `/tmp/ddtree_bench/{linear_asym3,ddtree_b12k2_asym3}.txt`.

